7–1280","1254–1300":"1254–1300","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1199–1265":"1199–1265","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1254":"1254","1265":"1265","1199":"1199","England":"England"},"en":{"1225–1270":"1225–1270","1227–1280":"1227–1280","1254–1300":"1254–1300","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1199–1265":"1199–1265","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1254":"1254","1265":"1265","1199":"1199","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wielher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Merwin, Trud.","perhaps a topographic name from Middle High German <i>wuol</i>, <i>wüele</i> ‘waterhole’ + <i>-er</i>.","habitational name for someone from a place called Wiehl or Wielen (see   Wiehl   and   Wiele  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiehl","meanings":["South German:","topographic name from Middle High German <i>wuol(lache)</i> ‘wallowing place’.","habitational name from any of the places called Wiehl, Wihl, or Wil in Germany and Switzerland."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Reduced form of Old Norse <i>Þorfriðr</i>, from <i>Þórr</i> (  see  Tor  ) + <i>friðr</i> ‘peace’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Richard Wielher was born in 1225, in England, his father, Lord Charles Thomas Wielher II, was 27 and his mother, Ruth Ann Williams, was 26. He married Rachel Lynn Wilks in 1253, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1270, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1225–1270":"1225–1270","1227–1280":"1227–1280","1254–1300":"1254–1300","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1199–1265":"1199–1265","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"122